As such, enormous efforts over the past few decades have been devoted to their (and enantioselective) synthesis.[1–2] In 2004, Fu and Suárez reported mild conditions for the two-carbon elongation of alkyne using ethyl diazoacetate, and they found the formed alkynoate could be isomerized to the corresponding allenoate.[3] Based on this useful transformation, advances have been made in this field.[4] For example, Tan and Huang reported the 3-alkynoate can be isomerized into chiral allene using a chiral guanidine.[5] From a reactivity standpoint, Sun reported several cascade reactions of allenoate, including the use of Adv. Abstract: An isochromene synthesis is developed utilizing a cascade reaction involving a CuI cata- lyzed coupling reaction between an alkyne and diazoacetate followed by allenoate isomerization and subsequent oxa-Michael addition. The cascade sequence was also demonstrated for the synthesis of naphthalenes. Furthermore, the methodology devel- oped herein was applied toward a stereoselective synthesis of pyranonaphthoquinone kalafungin. This serendipitous discovery guided us to further develop this reaction and its application on pyrano- naphthoquinone (PNQ) natural product.

Pyranonaphthoquinones are a large group of natural products named after its characteristic structural features, with the naphthoquinone and a trans-pyran ring in most cases (Figure 1).[9] Several dimeric natural products also have been isolated. These natural products have been found to be bioactive, including antibacterial, antifungal and anticancer activities, and they became synthetic targets since isolation.[10] For the synthesis of the natural products, formation of the pyran ring is most commonly prepared through oxa- Pictet-Spengler reaction utilizing trisubstituted benzene or naphthalene ring as precursor. Other strategies include Pd(II)-catalyzed alkoxycarbonylative annula- tion to generate cis-pyran-fused lactone have been developed by Semmelhack and further applied by Kraus and Yang respectively.[11] However, one of the straightforward strategies, intramolecular oxa-Michael Figure 1. With the optimized conditions established, efforts began to evaluate the substrate scope. Primary alcohol 1 b, secondary 1 c and 1 d were prepared and coupled with diazoacetate. the expected product was formed in good yield (Table 2, entries 1 to 3). Furthermore, two diazo esters 3 b and 3 c were prepared following Fukuyama’s procedure[14] and both were submitted to undergo the coupling with 1 a to 1 d. Gratifyingly, the corresponding isochromene products (2 e to 2 l) were formed (Table 2, entries 5 to 12). Substrates with either electron-withdrawing or elec- tron-donating group both afforded the products (Ta- ble 2, entries 13 and 14). Substrate 1 g, with tetrasub- stituted benzene ring (For the preparation of 1 g, see Scheme 2), dramatically improved the reaction profile with an increased equivalent of CuI (Table 2, entry 15). Given the high reactivity of the in-situ generated allenoate, several naphthalene products (2 q to 2 w) also can be formed under the reaction condition. It is also worth noting substates 1 m, 1 n and 1 o were synthesized as a mixture of Z/E configuration, and both can be transformed into the product in the reaction conditions. This transformation proceeds through 6π electrocyclization[16] (Table 3, entries 1–7). Building on the above collective results, the total synthesis of pyranonaphthoquinones was performed to verify its synthetic utility. Initially, substrate with tetra- substituted benzene ring was needed to be synthesized for the oxa-Michael addition. Moving forward from 6, the benzene quinone was formed through CAN oxidation, then Diels-Alder reaction with 1-(Trimethylsiloxy)-1,3-Bu- tadiene followed by Jones oxidation, naphthoquinone 7 was prepared. Following the established procedure, after hydrolysis of the ester under acidic condition, lactone formation[19] followed by acid-catalyzed epime- rization of cis-pyran, the natural product kalafungin was obtained. The 1H and 13C NMR was matched with the reported data.[21,22] Conclusions In summary, an in-situ allenoate formation and intra- molecular oxa-Michael cascade was developed for isochromene formation. This methodology was then applied to the total synthesis of kalafungin. Further methodology studies and enantioselective synthesis of dimeric pyranonaphthoquinones are currently under- way in our laboratory and will be reported in due course. General Procedure for Isochromene and Naphthalene Ring Formation

To a stirred solution of alkyne 1 (0.63 mmol) and CuI (24 mg, 0.13 mmol) in MeCN (3 mL) was added diazo reagent 3 a,3 b or 3 c (0.94 mmol). After stirred for 8 h at r.t. Et3N (0.44 mL, 3.15 mmol) was added and the mixture was stirred for another 8 h at r.t. The reaction mixture was directly concentrated, and the crude product was purified by flash column chromatography on silica to afford the desired target compound. Adv. Synth.
